##100,000 people petition for Queen'S REMOVAL FROM LONDON! UK Health Secretary responds to 'herd immunity' : It's not what you think

Micro Signal China Business Journal

Function introduction, grow in step with Chinese enterprises, talk with business leaders, spread business ideals, serve business people, "China Business News" control of the absolute voice of Chinese business.

According to the Department of Social Security, from 9:00 a.m. on March 14 to 9:00 a.m. on March 15, there were 232 new confirmed cases of pneumonia in the UK, bringing the total to 1,372; 14 new deaths and 35 cumulative deaths.

UK Outbreak Statistics (photo: Wind)

The Queen's Elizabeth II has temporarily moved out of Buckingham Palace to take refuge at Windsor Castle outside London because of the impending outbreak in the UK, CCTV news reported, citing British media. A spokesman for the Royal Family said Buckingham Palace, which has 500 staff in central London, was more potentially dangerous than any other royal estate. In the event of further deterioration in the UK, the soon to be 94 year old Elizabeth II and 98 year old Prince Philip of Swabia will be relocated to Sandringham, 200km from London.

But in the folk, the partial material shortage phenomenon already appeared. According to CCTV news, British people first rush to buy toilet paper and hand sanitizer, these goods are basically every day after shipment will be quickly bought away, and bread shelves, almost nothing to buy. Other items snapped up include eggs, milk, rice, noodles, cans, biscuits and frozen vegetables, all of which are very easy to store.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Photograph: CCTV News

For Britain, the world is more concerned about its government's epidemic prevention and control measures. The UK Health Secretary has offered a new explanation after a public outcry over "herd immunity" .

Health Secretary: "Herd Immunity" is not a goal or policy

"The new crown disease is the most serious public health crisis of our generation, " the prime minister, Boris Johnson, said at a news conference on March 12. "Frankly, more families will lose their loved ones. "

On the same day, Boris formally announced at a press conference that Britain had entered the second phase of the fight against the disease -- the "Delay" phase. In short, the UK's strategy is not to fight the disease, to allow it to progress slowly, and to expect that most people will have no symptoms or only mild symptoms after a latent infection, so that universal immunity can be achieved among the population to control the disease, it's called Herd immunity, and it's used to prevent and control COVID-19.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Herd immunity (image: Mount Hua Infection)

Boris's comments have also drawn attention.

"HIGH STAKES! " A Bskyb commentary criticized the herd-immunization strategy as risky; london-based veteran crisis care expert Symon Ashworth called on the government to "wake up" .

More than 100,000 people have signed the petition, calling on the British government to take a "more active approach" to stop the spread of the disease, CCTV News reported Monday. The petition says it is necessary for Britain to follow Italy's example by restricting all non-essential inter-town movements, as well as large gatherings. In Britain, where the number of petitioners exceeds 100,000, parliament should consider debating the issue.

In addition, more than 300 academics from the UK scientific community and more than 200 psychologists / behaviorists have issued open letters opposing the UK government's policy and questioning whether the goal of "herd immunity" can be achieved.

According to Bskyb News on the 15th, "Herd immunity is not our goal or policy -- it is a scientific concept -- our policy is to protect life and to fight this virus, " Hancock, the UK Health Secretary, said

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Photograph: Bskyb

Action: People over 70 will be asked to stay indoors

The British government has not been entirely inactive in its efforts to prevent and control the outbreak. Robert Peston, editor in chief of ITV politics, said the government would soon instruct people over the age of 70 to be placed in strict quarantine for four months, this is part of a plan to respond to the outbreak of new coronavirus pneumonia.

Peaston said the British government was likely to carry out "wartime" mobilisation in the next five to 20 days. Other planned measures include the compulsory expropriation of hotels and other facilities as temporary hospitals and the expropriation of private hospitals.

UK Health Secretary Hancock said: 'In the next few weeks people over 70 will be asked to stay indoors to protect themselves from coronavirus infection. '

According to the Daily Mail, further measures planned by the British government in response to the new outbreak of pneumonia include:

Deploy troops to hospitals and supermarkets;

Thousands of private hospital beds will be requisitioned to relieve pressure on the NHS;

Urge enterprises to expand production lines to produce basic medical equipment such as breathing machines for the benefit of the state;

If one member of a family is infected, the whole family will be isolated;

Britain's police are planning to release the police force by investigating only crimes involving personal safety rather than misdemeanors.

Is the "herd immunity" strategy working?

So is the UK's concept of "herd immunity" on track? Zhang Wenhong, director of the hospital infection department of Mount Hua Hospital, said in his public wechat message on Mount Hua infection that,

It's based on a theory. The first is the theory of epidemiology -- that universal immunity can form a steady state. In fact, most of the infected patients are asymptomatic or only mild, and can be cured by self-limited treatment without treatment or symptomatic treatment, the British government also reiterated at the press conference that the death rate for the new crown is 1% . Therefore, by opening up the prevention and control of the epidemic, allowing a large number of people to recover from infection and acquire immunity, and then concentrating medical efforts on treating the critically ill in the population, that is, not spending the cost of preventing "infection" , and spend all your money on death prevention. This is the logic behind the UK strategy to contain the epidemic without sacrificing social dynamism and economic development to stringent control measures, and to minimise the cost of fighting it.

But there is still a lot of uncertainty about whether such a "herd immunity" approach, which seems theoretically feasible, will actually succeed.

From China's experience, China has gone to great lengths to protect its citizens from infection, and at the expense of the economy in prevention and control, has rapidly reduced the spread of the virus within communities in a short period of time, and has quickly restored social order, to try to restore socio-economic development. But because of the strong determination of the Chinese state and the cooperation of its people, this is not something that other countries can copy.
